#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:6
msgid "pytest fixtures: explicit, modular, scalable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:16
msgid ""
"The `purpose of test fixtures`_ is to provide a fixed baseline upon which "
"tests can reliably and repeatedly execute.   pytest fixtures offer dramatic "
"improvements over the classic xUnit style of setup/teardown functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:21
msgid ""
"fixtures have explicit names and are activated by declaring their use from "
"test functions, modules, classes or whole projects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:24
msgid ""
"fixtures are implemented in a modular manner, as each fixture name triggers "
"a *fixture function* which can itself use other fixtures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:27
msgid ""
"fixture management scales from simple unit to complex functional testing, "
"allowing to parametrize fixtures and tests according to configuration and "
"component options, or to re-use fixtures across class, module or whole test "
"session scopes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:32
msgid ""
"In addition, pytest continues to support :ref:`xunitsetup`.  You can mix "
"both styles, moving incrementally from classic to new style, as you prefer.  "
"You can also start out from existing :ref:`unittest.TestCase style <unittest."
"TestCase>` or :ref:`nose based <nosestyle>` projects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:39
msgid ""
"pytest-2.4 introduced an additional :ref:`yield fixture mechanism "
"<yieldfixture>` for easier context manager integration and more linear "
"writing of teardown code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:50
msgid "Fixtures as Function arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:52
msgid ""
"Test functions can receive fixture objects by naming them as an input "
"argument. For each argument name, a fixture function with that name provides "
"the fixture object.  Fixture functions are registered by marking them with :"
"py:func:`@pytest.fixture <_pytest.python.fixture>`.  Let's look at a simple "
"self-contained test module containing a fixture and a test function using "
"it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:59
msgid ""
"# content of ./test_smtpsimple.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def smtp():\n"
"    import smtplib\n"
"    return smtplib.SMTP(\"smtp.gmail.com\")\n"
"\n"
"def test_ehlo(smtp):\n"
"    response, msg = smtp.ehlo()\n"
"    assert response == 250\n"
"    assert 0 # for demo purposes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:72
msgid ""
"Here, the ``test_ehlo`` needs the ``smtp`` fixture value.  pytest will "
"discover and call the :py:func:`@pytest.fixture <_pytest.python.fixture>` "
"marked ``smtp`` fixture function.  Running the test looks like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:76
msgid ""
"$ py.test test_smtpsimple.py\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 1 items\n"
"\n"
"test_smtpsimple.py F\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_ehlo ________\n"
"\n"
"smtp = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_ehlo(smtp):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp.ehlo()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
">       assert 0 # for demo purposes\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_smtpsimple.py:11: AssertionError\n"
"======= 1 failed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:98
msgid ""
"In the failure traceback we see that the test function was called with a "
"``smtp`` argument, the ``smtplib.SMTP()`` instance created by the fixture "
"function.  The test function fails on our deliberate ``assert 0``.  Here is "
"the exact protocol used by ``pytest`` to call the test function this way:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:103
msgid ""
"pytest :ref:`finds <test discovery>` the ``test_ehlo`` because of the "
"``test_`` prefix.  The test function needs a function argument named "
"``smtp``.  A matching fixture function is discovered by looking for a "
"fixture-marked function named ``smtp``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:108
msgid "``smtp()`` is called to create an instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:110
msgid ""
"``test_ehlo(<SMTP instance>)`` is called and fails in the last line of the "
"test function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:113
msgid ""
"Note that if you misspell a function argument or want to use one that isn't "
"available, you'll see an error with a list of available function arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:119
msgid "You can always issue::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:121
msgid "py.test --fixtures test_simplefactory.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:123
msgid "to see available fixtures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:125
msgid ""
"In versions prior to 2.3 there was no ``@pytest.fixture`` marker and you had "
"to use a magic ``pytest_funcarg__NAME`` prefix for the fixture factory.  "
"This remains and will remain supported but is not anymore advertised as the "
"primary means of declaring fixture functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:132
msgid "\"Funcargs\" a prime example of dependency injection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:134
msgid ""
"When injecting fixtures to test functions, pytest-2.0 introduced the term "
"\"funcargs\" or \"funcarg mechanism\" which continues to be present also in "
"docs today.  It now refers to the specific case of injecting fixture values "
"as arguments to test functions.  With pytest-2.3 there are more "
"possibilities to use fixtures but \"funcargs\" remain as the main way as "
"they allow to directly state the dependencies of a test function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:141
msgid ""
"As the following examples show in more detail, funcargs allow test functions "
"to easily receive and work against specific pre-initialized application "
"objects without having to care about import/setup/cleanup details.  It's a "
"prime example of `dependency injection`_ where fixture functions take the "
"role of the *injector* and test functions are the *consumers* of fixture "
"objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:151
msgid "Sharing a fixture across tests in a module (or class/session)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:155
msgid ""
"Fixtures requiring network access depend on connectivity and are usually "
"time-expensive to create.  Extending the previous example, we can add a "
"``scope='module'`` parameter to the :py:func:`@pytest.fixture <_pytest."
"python.fixture>` invocation to cause the decorated ``smtp`` fixture function "
"to only be invoked once per test module.  Multiple test functions in a test "
"module will thus each receive the same ``smtp`` fixture instance.  The next "
"example puts the fixture function into a separate ``conftest.py`` file so "
"that tests from multiple test modules in the directory can access the "
"fixture function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:166
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import smtplib\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def smtp():\n"
"    return smtplib.SMTP(\"smtp.gmail.com\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:174
msgid ""
"The name of the fixture again is ``smtp`` and you can access its result by "
"listing the name ``smtp`` as an input parameter in any test or fixture "
"function (in or below the directory where ``conftest.py`` is located)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:178
msgid ""
"# content of test_module.py\n"
"\n"
"def test_ehlo(smtp):\n"
"    response, msg = smtp.ehlo()\n"
"    assert response == 250\n"
"    assert b\"smtp.gmail.com\" in msg\n"
"    assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"\n"
"def test_noop(smtp):\n"
"    response, msg = smtp.noop()\n"
"    assert response == 250\n"
"    assert 0  # for demo purposes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:191
msgid ""
"We deliberately insert failing ``assert 0`` statements in order to inspect "
"what is going on and can now run the tests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:194
msgid ""
"$ py.test test_module.py\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 2 items\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py FF\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_ehlo ________\n"
"\n"
"smtp = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_ehlo(smtp):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp.ehlo()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
"        assert b\"smtp.gmail.com\" in msg\n"
">       assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"_______ test_noop ________\n"
"\n"
"smtp = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_noop(smtp):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp.noop()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
">       assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py:11: AssertionError\n"
"======= 2 failed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:228
msgid ""
"You see the two ``assert 0`` failing and more importantly you can also see "
"that the same (module-scoped) ``smtp`` object was passed into the two test "
"functions because pytest shows the incoming argument values in the "
"traceback.  As a result, the two test functions using ``smtp`` run as quick "
"as a single one because they reuse the same instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:234
msgid ""
"If you decide that you rather want to have a session-scoped ``smtp`` "
"instance, you can simply declare it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:237
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\")\n"
"def smtp(...):\n"
"    # the returned fixture value will be shared for\n"
"    # all tests needing it"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:247
msgid "Fixture finalization / executing teardown code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:249
msgid ""
"pytest supports execution of fixture specific finalization code when the "
"fixture goes out of scope.  By accepting a ``request`` object into your "
"fixture function you can call its ``request.addfinalizer`` one or multiple "
"times::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:254
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import smtplib\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def smtp(request):\n"
"    smtp = smtplib.SMTP(\"smtp.gmail.com\")\n"
"    def fin():\n"
"        print (\"teardown smtp\")\n"
"        smtp.close()\n"
"    request.addfinalizer(fin)\n"
"    return smtp  # provide the fixture value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:268
msgid ""
"The ``fin`` function will execute when the last test using the fixture in "
"the module has finished execution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:271
msgid "Let's execute it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:273
msgid ""
"$ py.test -s -q --tb=no\n"
"FFteardown smtp\n"
"\n"
"2 failed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:278
msgid ""
"We see that the ``smtp`` instance is finalized after the two tests finished "
"execution.  Note that if we decorated our fixture function with "
"``scope='function'`` then fixture setup and cleanup would occur around each "
"single test.  In either case the test module itself does not need to change "
"or know about these details of fixture setup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:287
msgid "Finalization/teardown with yield fixtures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:289
msgid ""
"Another alternative to the *request.addfinalizer()* method is to use *yield "
"fixtures*. All the code after the *yield* statement serves as the teardown "
"code. See the :ref:`yield fixture documentation <yieldfixture>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:297
msgid "Fixtures can introspect the requesting test context"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:299
msgid ""
"Fixture function can accept the :py:class:`request <FixtureRequest>` object "
"to introspect the \"requesting\" test function, class or module context. "
"Further extending the previous ``smtp`` fixture example, let's read an "
"optional server URL from the test module which uses our fixture::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:304
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import smtplib\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def smtp(request):\n"
"    server = getattr(request.module, \"smtpserver\", \"smtp.gmail.com\")\n"
"    smtp = smtplib.SMTP(server)\n"
"\n"
"    def fin():\n"
"        print (\"finalizing %s (%s)\" % (smtp, server))\n"
"        smtp.close()\n"
"    request.addfinalizer(fin)\n"
"    return smtp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:319
msgid ""
"We use the ``request.module`` attribute to optionally obtain an "
"``smtpserver`` attribute from the test module.  If we just execute again, "
"nothing much has changed::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:323
msgid ""
"$ py.test -s -q --tb=no\n"
"FFfinalizing <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef> (smtp.gmail.com)\n"
"\n"
"2 failed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:328
msgid ""
"Let's quickly create another test module that actually sets the server URL "
"in its module namespace::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:331
msgid ""
"# content of test_anothersmtp.py\n"
"\n"
"smtpserver = \"mail.python.org\"  # will be read by smtp fixture\n"
"\n"
"def test_showhelo(smtp):\n"
"    assert 0, smtp.helo()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:338
msgid "Running it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:340
msgid ""
"$ py.test -qq --tb=short test_anothersmtp.py\n"
"F\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_showhelo ________\n"
"test_anothersmtp.py:5: in test_showhelo\n"
"    assert 0, smtp.helo()\n"
"E   AssertionError: (250, b'mail.python.org')\n"
"E   assert 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:349
msgid ""
"voila! The ``smtp`` fixture function picked up our mail server name from the "
"module namespace."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:355
msgid "Parametrizing a fixture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:357
msgid ""
"Fixture functions can be parametrized in which case they will be called "
"multiple times, each time executing the set of dependent tests, i. e. the "
"tests that depend on this fixture.  Test functions do usually not need to be "
"aware of their re-running.  Fixture parametrization helps to write "
"exhaustive functional tests for components which themselves can be "
"configured in multiple ways."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:364
msgid ""
"Extending the previous example, we can flag the fixture to create two "
"``smtp`` fixture instances which will cause all tests using the fixture to "
"run twice.  The fixture function gets access to each parameter through the "
"special :py:class:`request <FixtureRequest>` object::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:369
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import smtplib\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\",\n"
"                params=[\"smtp.gmail.com\", \"mail.python.org\"])\n"
"def smtp(request):\n"
"    smtp = smtplib.SMTP(request.param)\n"
"    def fin():\n"
"        print (\"finalizing %s\" % smtp)\n"
"        smtp.close()\n"
"    request.addfinalizer(fin)\n"
"    return smtp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:383
msgid ""
"The main change is the declaration of ``params`` with :py:func:`@pytest."
"fixture <_pytest.python.fixture>`, a list of values for each of which the "
"fixture function will execute and can access a value via ``request.param``.  "
"No test function code needs to change. So let's just do another run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:389
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q test_module.py\n"
"FFFF\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_ehlo[smtp.gmail.com] ________\n"
"\n"
"smtp = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_ehlo(smtp):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp.ehlo()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
"        assert b\"smtp.gmail.com\" in msg\n"
">       assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"_______ test_noop[smtp.gmail.com] ________\n"
"\n"
"smtp = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_noop(smtp):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp.noop()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
">       assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py:11: AssertionError\n"
"_______ test_ehlo[mail.python.org] ________\n"
"\n"
"smtp = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_ehlo(smtp):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp.ehlo()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
">       assert b\"smtp.gmail.com\" in msg\n"
"E       assert b'smtp.gmail.com' in b'mail.python.org\\nSIZE "
"51200000\\nETRN\\nSTARTTLS\\nENHANCEDSTATUSCODES\\n8BITMIME\\nDSN\\nSMTPUTF8'\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py:5: AssertionError\n"
"-------------------------- Captured stdout setup "
"---------------------------\n"
"finalizing <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"_______ test_noop[mail.python.org] ________\n"
"\n"
"smtp = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_noop(smtp):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp.noop()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
">       assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py:11: AssertionError\n"
"4 failed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:441
msgid ""
"We see that our two test functions each ran twice, against the different "
"``smtp`` instances.  Note also, that with the ``mail.python.org`` connection "
"the second test fails in ``test_ehlo`` because a different server string is "
"expected than what arrived."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:446
msgid ""
"pytest will build a string that is the test ID for each fixture value in a "
"parametrized fixture, e.g. ``test_ehlo[smtp.gmail.com]`` and "
"``test_ehlo[mail.python.org]`` in the above examples.  These IDs can be used "
"with ``-k`` to select specific cases to run, and they will also identify the "
"specific case when one is failing.  Running pytest with ``--collect-only`` "
"will show the generated IDs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:453
msgid ""
"Numbers, strings, booleans and None will have their usual string "
"representation used in the test ID. For other objects, pytest will make a "
"string based on the argument name.  It is possible to customise the string "
"used in a test ID for a certain fixture value by using the ``ids`` keyword "
"argument::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:459
msgid ""
"# content of test_ids.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(params=[0, 1], ids=[\"spam\", \"ham\"])\n"
"def a(request):\n"
"    return request.param\n"
"\n"
"def test_a(a):\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"def idfn(fixture_value):\n"
"    if fixture_value == 0:\n"
"        return \"eggs\"\n"
"    else:\n"
"        return None\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(params=[0, 1], ids=idfn)\n"
"def b(request):\n"
"    return request.param\n"
"\n"
"def test_b(b):\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:482
msgid ""
"The above shows how ``ids`` can be either a list of strings to use or a "
"function which will be called with the fixture value and then has to return "
"a string to use.  In the latter case if the function return ``None`` then "
"pytest's auto-generated ID will be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:487
msgid "Running the above tests results in the following test IDs being used::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:489
msgid ""
"$ py.test --collect-only\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 10 items\n"
"<Module 'test_anothersmtp.py'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_showhelo[smtp.gmail.com]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_showhelo[mail.python.org]'>\n"
"<Module 'test_ids.py'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_a[spam]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_a[ham]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_b[eggs]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_b[1]'>\n"
"<Module 'test_module.py'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_ehlo[smtp.gmail.com]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_noop[smtp.gmail.com]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_ehlo[mail.python.org]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_noop[mail.python.org]'>\n"
"\n"
"======= no tests ran in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:513
msgid "Modularity: using fixtures from a fixture function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:515
msgid ""
"You can not only use fixtures in test functions but fixture functions can "
"use other fixtures themselves.  This contributes to a modular design of your "
"fixtures and allows re-use of framework-specific fixtures across many "
"projects.  As a simple example, we can extend the previous example and "
"instantiate an object ``app`` where we stick the already defined ``smtp`` "
"resource into it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:522
msgid ""
"# content of test_appsetup.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"class App:\n"
"    def __init__(self, smtp):\n"
"        self.smtp = smtp\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def app(smtp):\n"
"    return App(smtp)\n"
"\n"
"def test_smtp_exists(app):\n"
"    assert app.smtp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:537
msgid ""
"Here we declare an ``app`` fixture which receives the previously defined "
"``smtp`` fixture and instantiates an ``App`` object with it.  Let's run it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:540
msgid ""
"$ py.test -v test_appsetup.py\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 2 items\n"
"\n"
"test_appsetup.py::test_smtp_exists[smtp.gmail.com] PASSED\n"
"test_appsetup.py::test_smtp_exists[mail.python.org] PASSED\n"
"\n"
"======= 2 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:552
msgid ""
"Due to the parametrization of ``smtp`` the test will run twice with two "
"different ``App`` instances and respective smtp servers.  There is no need "
"for the ``app`` fixture to be aware of the ``smtp`` parametrization as "
"pytest will fully analyse the fixture dependency graph."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:557
msgid ""
"Note, that the ``app`` fixture has a scope of ``module`` and uses a module-"
"scoped ``smtp`` fixture.  The example would still work if ``smtp`` was "
"cached on a ``session`` scope: it is fine for fixtures to use \"broader\" "
"scoped fixtures but not the other way round: A session-scoped fixture could "
"not use a module-scoped one in a meaningful way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:568
msgid "Automatic grouping of tests by fixture instances"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:572
msgid ""
"pytest minimizes the number of active fixtures during test runs. If you have "
"a parametrized fixture, then all the tests using it will first execute with "
"one instance and then finalizers are called before the next fixture instance "
"is created.  Among other things, this eases testing of applications which "
"create and use global state."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:578
msgid ""
"The following example uses two parametrized funcargs, one of which is scoped "
"on a per-module basis, and all the functions perform ``print`` calls to show "
"the setup/teardown flow::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:582
msgid ""
"# content of test_module.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\", params=[\"mod1\", \"mod2\"])\n"
"def modarg(request):\n"
"    param = request.param\n"
"    print (\"  SETUP modarg %s\" % param)\n"
"    def fin():\n"
"        print (\"  TEARDOWN modarg %s\" % param)\n"
"    request.addfinalizer(fin)\n"
"    return param\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"function\", params=[1,2])\n"
"def otherarg(request):\n"
"    param = request.param\n"
"    print (\"  SETUP otherarg %s\" % param)\n"
"    def fin():\n"
"        print (\"  TEARDOWN otherarg %s\" % param)\n"
"    request.addfinalizer(fin)\n"
"    return param\n"
"\n"
"def test_0(otherarg):\n"
"    print (\"  RUN test0 with otherarg %s\" % otherarg)\n"
"def test_1(modarg):\n"
"    print (\"  RUN test1 with modarg %s\" % modarg)\n"
"def test_2(otherarg, modarg):\n"
"    print (\"  RUN test2 with otherarg %s and modarg %s\" % (otherarg, "
"modarg))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:611
msgid ""
"Let's run the tests in verbose mode and with looking at the print-output::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:613
msgid ""
"$ py.test -v -s test_module.py\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1 -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python3.5\n"
"cachedir: .cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collecting ... collected 8 items\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py::test_0[1]   SETUP otherarg 1\n"
"  RUN test0 with otherarg 1\n"
"PASSED  TEARDOWN otherarg 1\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py::test_0[2]   SETUP otherarg 2\n"
"  RUN test0 with otherarg 2\n"
"PASSED  TEARDOWN otherarg 2\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py::test_1[mod1]   SETUP modarg mod1\n"
"  RUN test1 with modarg mod1\n"
"PASSED\n"
"test_module.py::test_2[1-mod1]   SETUP otherarg 1\n"
"  RUN test2 with otherarg 1 and modarg mod1\n"
"PASSED  TEARDOWN otherarg 1\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py::test_2[2-mod1]   SETUP otherarg 2\n"
"  RUN test2 with otherarg 2 and modarg mod1\n"
"PASSED  TEARDOWN otherarg 2\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py::test_1[mod2]   TEARDOWN modarg mod1\n"
"  SETUP modarg mod2\n"
"  RUN test1 with modarg mod2\n"
"PASSED\n"
"test_module.py::test_2[1-mod2]   SETUP otherarg 1\n"
"  RUN test2 with otherarg 1 and modarg mod2\n"
"PASSED  TEARDOWN otherarg 1\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py::test_2[2-mod2]   SETUP otherarg 2\n"
"  RUN test2 with otherarg 2 and modarg mod2\n"
"PASSED  TEARDOWN otherarg 2\n"
"  TEARDOWN modarg mod2\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"======= 8 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:655
msgid ""
"You can see that the parametrized module-scoped ``modarg`` resource caused "
"an ordering of test execution that lead to the fewest possible \"active\" "
"resources. The finalizer for the ``mod1`` parametrized resource was executed "
"before the ``mod2`` resource was setup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:660
msgid ""
"In particular notice that test_0 is completely independent and finishes "
"first. Then test_1 is executed with ``mod1``, then test_2 with ``mod1``, "
"then test_1 with ``mod2`` and finally test_2 with ``mod2``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:664
msgid ""
"The ``otherarg`` parametrized resource (having function scope) was set up "
"before and teared down after every test that used it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:671
msgid "Using fixtures from classes, modules or projects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:675
msgid ""
"Sometimes test functions do not directly need access to a fixture object. "
"For example, tests may require to operate with an empty directory as the "
"current working directory but otherwise do not care for the concrete "
"directory.  Here is how you can can use the standard `tempfile <http://docs."
"python.org/library/tempfile.html>`_ and pytest fixtures to achieve it.  We "
"separate the creation of the fixture into a conftest.py file::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:683
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import tempfile\n"
"import os\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture()\n"
"def cleandir():\n"
"    newpath = tempfile.mkdtemp()\n"
"    os.chdir(newpath)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:694
msgid "and declare its use in a test module via a ``usefixtures`` marker::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:696
msgid ""
"# content of test_setenv.py\n"
"import os\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.usefixtures(\"cleandir\")\n"
"class TestDirectoryInit:\n"
"    def test_cwd_starts_empty(self):\n"
"        assert os.listdir(os.getcwd()) == []\n"
"        with open(\"myfile\", \"w\") as f:\n"
"            f.write(\"hello\")\n"
"\n"
"    def test_cwd_again_starts_empty(self):\n"
"        assert os.listdir(os.getcwd()) == []"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:710
msgid ""
"Due to the ``usefixtures`` marker, the ``cleandir`` fixture will be required "
"for the execution of each test method, just as if you specified a "
"\"cleandir\" function argument to each of them.  Let's run it to verify our "
"fixture is activated and the tests pass::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:715 ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:795
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q\n"
"..\n"
"2 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:719
msgid "You can specify multiple fixtures like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:721
msgid "@pytest.mark.usefixtures(\"cleandir\", \"anotherfixture\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:725
msgid ""
"and you may specify fixture usage at the test module level, using a generic "
"feature of the mark mechanism:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:728
msgid "pytestmark = pytest.mark.usefixtures(\"cleandir\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:732
msgid ""
"Note that the assigned variable *must* be called ``pytestmark``, assigning e."
"g. ``foomark`` will not activate the fixtures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:735
msgid ""
"Lastly you can put fixtures required by all tests in your project into an "
"ini-file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:738
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.ini\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"usefixtures = cleandir"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:749
msgid "Autouse fixtures (xUnit setup on steroids)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:753
msgid ""
"Occasionally, you may want to have fixtures get invoked automatically "
"without a `usefixtures`_ or `funcargs`_ reference.   As a practical example, "
"suppose we have a database fixture which has a begin/rollback/commit "
"architecture and we want to automatically surround each test method by a "
"transaction and a rollback.  Here is a dummy self-contained implementation "
"of this idea::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:760
msgid ""
"# content of test_db_transact.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"class DB:\n"
"    def __init__(self):\n"
"        self.intransaction = []\n"
"    def begin(self, name):\n"
"        self.intransaction.append(name)\n"
"    def rollback(self):\n"
"        self.intransaction.pop()\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def db():\n"
"    return DB()\n"
"\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    @pytest.fixture(autouse=True)\n"
"    def transact(self, request, db):\n"
"        db.begin(request.function.__name__)\n"
"        request.addfinalizer(db.rollback)\n"
"\n"
"    def test_method1(self, db):\n"
"        assert db.intransaction == [\"test_method1\"]\n"
"\n"
"    def test_method2(self, db):\n"
"        assert db.intransaction == [\"test_method2\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:788
msgid ""
"The class-level ``transact`` fixture is marked with *autouse=true* which "
"implies that all test methods in the class will use this fixture without a "
"need to state it in the test function signature or with a class-level "
"``usefixtures`` decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:793
msgid "If we run it, we get two passing tests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:799
msgid "Here is how autouse fixtures work in other scopes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:801
msgid ""
"if an autouse fixture is defined in a test module, all its test functions "
"automatically use it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:804
msgid ""
"if an autouse fixture is defined in a conftest.py file then all tests in all "
"test modules below its directory will invoke the fixture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:807
msgid ""
"lastly, and **please use that with care**: if you define an autouse fixture "
"in a plugin, it will be invoked for all tests in all projects where the "
"plugin is installed.  This can be useful if a fixture only anyway works in "
"the presence of certain settings e. g. in the ini-file.  Such a global "
"fixture should always quickly determine if it should do any work and avoid "
"otherwise expensive imports or computation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:814
msgid ""
"Note that the above ``transact`` fixture may very well be a fixture that you "
"want to make available in your project without having it generally active.  "
"The canonical way to do that is to put the transact definition into a "
"conftest.py file **without** using ``autouse``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:819
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"@pytest.fixture()\n"
"def transact(self, request, db):\n"
"    db.begin()\n"
"    request.addfinalizer(db.rollback)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:825
msgid "and then e.g. have a TestClass using it by declaring the need::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:827
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.usefixtures(\"transact\")\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    def test_method1(self):\n"
"        ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:832
msgid ""
"All test methods in this TestClass will use the transaction fixture while "
"other test classes or functions in the module will not use it unless they "
"also add a ``transact`` reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:837
msgid "Shifting (visibility of) fixture functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:839
msgid ""
"If during implementing your tests you realize that you want to use a fixture "
"function from multiple test files you can move it to a :ref:`conftest.py "
"<conftest.py>` file or even separately installable :ref:`plugins <plugins>` "
"without changing test code.  The discovery of fixtures functions starts at "
"test classes, then test modules, then ``conftest.py`` files and finally "
"builtin and third party plugins."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:847
msgid "Overriding fixtures on various levels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:849
msgid ""
"In relatively large test suite, you most likely need to ``override`` a "
"``global`` or ``root`` fixture with a ``locally`` defined one, keeping the "
"test code readable and maintainable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:853
msgid "Override a fixture on a folder (conftest) level"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:855 ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:898
#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:939 ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:977
msgid "Given the tests file structure is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:859
msgid ""
"tests/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"\n"
"    conftest.py\n"
"        # content of tests/conftest.py\n"
"        import pytest\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.fixture\n"
"        def username():\n"
"            return 'username'\n"
"\n"
"    test_something.py\n"
"        # content of tests/test_something.py\n"
"        def test_username(username):\n"
"            assert username == 'username'\n"
"\n"
"    subfolder/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"\n"
"        conftest.py\n"
"            # content of tests/subfolder/conftest.py\n"
"            import pytest\n"
"\n"
"            @pytest.fixture\n"
"            def username(username):\n"
"                return 'overridden-' + username\n"
"\n"
"        test_something.py\n"
"            # content of tests/subfolder/test_something.py\n"
"            def test_username(username):\n"
"                assert username == 'overridden-username'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:891
msgid ""
"As you can see, a fixture with the same name can be overridden for certain "
"test folder level. Note that the ``base`` or ``super`` fixture can be "
"accessed from the ``overriding`` fixture easily - used in the example above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:896
msgid "Override a fixture on a test module level"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:902
msgid ""
"tests/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"\n"
"    conftest.py\n"
"        # content of tests/conftest.py\n"
"        @pytest.fixture\n"
"        def username():\n"
"            return 'username'\n"
"\n"
"    test_something.py\n"
"        # content of tests/test_something.py\n"
"        import pytest\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.fixture\n"
"        def username(username):\n"
"            return 'overridden-' + username\n"
"\n"
"        def test_username(username):\n"
"            assert username == 'overridden-username'\n"
"\n"
"    test_something_else.py\n"
"        # content of tests/test_something_else.py\n"
"        import pytest\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.fixture\n"
"        def username(username):\n"
"            return 'overridden-else-' + username\n"
"\n"
"        def test_username(username):\n"
"            assert username == 'overridden-else-username'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:933
msgid ""
"In the example above, a fixture with the same name can be overridden for "
"certain test module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:937
msgid "Override a fixture with direct test parametrization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:943
msgid ""
"tests/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"\n"
"    conftest.py\n"
"        # content of tests/conftest.py\n"
"        import pytest\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.fixture\n"
"        def username():\n"
"            return 'username'\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.fixture\n"
"        def other_username(username):\n"
"            return 'other-' + username\n"
"\n"
"    test_something.py\n"
"        # content of tests/test_something.py\n"
"        import pytest\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.mark.parametrize('username', ['directly-overridden-"
"username'])\n"
"        def test_username(username):\n"
"            assert username == 'directly-overridden-username'\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.mark.parametrize('username', ['directly-overridden-username-"
"other'])\n"
"        def test_username_other(other_username):\n"
"            assert username == 'other-directly-overridden-username-other'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:970
msgid ""
"In the example above, a fixture value is overridden by the test parameter "
"value. Note that the value of the fixture can be overridden this way even if "
"the test doesn't use it directly (doesn't mention it in the function "
"prototype)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:975
msgid ""
"Override a parametrized fixture with non-parametrized one and vice versa"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:981
msgid ""
"tests/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"\n"
"    conftest.py\n"
"        # content of tests/conftest.py\n"
"        import pytest\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.fixture(params=['one', 'two', 'three'])\n"
"        def parametrized_username(request):\n"
"            return request.param\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.fixture\n"
"        def non_parametrized_username(request):\n"
"            return 'username'\n"
"\n"
"    test_something.py\n"
"        # content of tests/test_something.py\n"
"        import pytest\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.fixture\n"
"        def parametrized_username():\n"
"            return 'overridden-username'\n"
"\n"
"        @pytest.fixture(params=['one', 'two', 'three'])\n"
"        def non_parametrized_username(request):\n"
"            return request.param\n"
"\n"
"        def test_username(parametrized_username):\n"
"            assert parametrized_username == 'overridden-username'\n"
"\n"
"        def test_parametrized_username(non_parametrized_username):\n"
"            assert non_parametrized_username in ['one', 'two', 'three']\n"
"\n"
"    test_something_else.py\n"
"        # content of tests/test_something_else.py\n"
"        def test_username(parametrized_username):\n"
"            assert parametrized_username in ['one', 'two', 'three']\n"
"\n"
"        def test_username(non_parametrized_username):\n"
"            assert non_parametrized_username == 'username'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:1022
msgid ""
"In the example above, a parametrized fixture is overridden with a non-"
"parametrized version, and a non-parametrized fixture is overridden with a "
"parametrized version for certain test module. The same applies for the test "
"folder level obviously."
msgstr ""
